 carry out 10-fold dilutions of the sample until there is no more detectable DNA left. The point at which there is no DNA left is called the experimental end-point, and the titer of the original sample is simply the inverse of the dilution factor at the end-point. Check out hemagglutination(HA) in the context of virology. I think a method similar to this would be better than simply eyeballing the intensity of bands, because you will have some quantitative evidence."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f59bbb90d826f21c58f4f33c7d61e552?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19614,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19614/donjulian","reputation":379,"display_name":"DonJulian"},"score":0,"post_id":41787,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f524f51edb2e0e559de5f027217b2d47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14815,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14815/ro-siv","reputation":535,"display_name":"Ro Siv","accept_rate":97},"edited":false,"creation_date":1451164618,"comment_id":71090,"body":"If you want to eye-ball, you should use control bands at several different concentrations, so that you can say, &#39;the intensity of the band falls between control bands A and B, and so the concentratin of the sample is between concentrations A and B&#39;."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f524f51edb2e0e559de5f027217b2d47?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14815,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14815/ro-siv","reputation":535,"display_name":"Ro Siv","accept_rate":97},"score":0,"post_id":41787,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451164844,"comment_id":71091,"body":"My lab skills are lacking and I feel like I would mess up easily, do you have any &quot;dummy&quot; sources for doing the serial dilutions or using the imaging software?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f59bbb90