"last_activity_date":1450850771,"creation_date":1450850771,"body":"<p>Citing wikipedia:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_delivery\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gene delivery<\/a> is the process of introducing foreign DNA into host cells.<\/p>\n  \n  <p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_therapy\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gene therapy<\/a> is the therapeutic delivery of nucleic acid polymers into a patient's cells as a drug to treat disease.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>In other words, 'gene therapy' refers to the use of 'gene delivery' for therapeutic goals. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41706,"question_id":41705,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41705/difference-between-gene-delivery-and-gene-therapy","last_activity_date":1450850771,"creation_date":1450849481,"answer_count":1,"title":"Difference Between Gene Delivery and Gene Therapy","body":"<p>What is the specific difference between gene delivery and gene therapy? <\/p>\n\n<p>As far as I understand, gene delivery is the first step of gene therapy, but where does gene delivery end and gene therapy begin?<\/p>\n\n<p>Does gene therapy necessarily imply that the host DNA is itself changed, or is it just that there is \"extra\" DNA floating around with the host DNA that also gets replicated?<\/p>\n","question_id":41705,"tags":["genetics","gene-therapy"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":26,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f6357aa80c2c94eb752654201e732871?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16985,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16985/wythagoras","reputation":201,"display_name":"wythagoras"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41697,"edited":false