tivity is then relayed (via the <em>differential amplifier<\/em> technique) to a powerful amplifiers. Modern EEG amplifiers have very large input impedances, and are thus able to amplify these weak signals. However, it still only observes mass action of large groups of neurons, not e.g. single action potentials by single cells.<\/p>\n\n<p>Next, direct EEG analysis is comparatively uninformative for many reasons, including those you mention: that the scalp, the skull, and the other intervening tissue attenuate the signal. Thus, very often, extensive preprocessing is applied, such as averaging over many recordings. However, at least two features are already visible in the waking EEG. The first is the power-law structure of the frequency spectrum (although this is reinforced by the filtering characteristics of the tissue; the tissue filters higher frequencies more than lower ones). The second is the alpha wave, which is a large activity pattern coming mostly from visual areas. However, this is a very coarse feature; it tells us little beyond if the subject has their eyes open and is attentive, or has them closed/is inattentive.<\/p>\n\n<p>Lastly, it is indeed generally assumed that deep sources (such as subcortical areas) are not picked up by the EEG (but only by e.g. MEG).<\/p>\n\n<p>A good introduction to the topic is the book <em>Electroencephalography<\/em> by Niedermeyer and Lopes da Silva.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41699,"question_id":41690,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450820983,"comment_id":70918,"body":"&quot;Hence, the magic hat of an electrophysiologist is needed to extract the signal on the scalp from the noise by using noise reduction techniques such as signal averaging and filtering&quot; Don&#39;t overstate this - alpha waves are readily observable in raw EEG traces baring any filtering or averaging."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450821322,"comment_id":70920,"body":"I&#39;d phrase it as saying that to display specific, complex neural patterns, such techniques are necessary; but try to avoid the impression that you could not observe any neural activity at all without them. Alpha is important, clearly neural, and easily observable."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450822093,"comment_id":70921,"body":"@user49102 - given the level of knowledge of OP I do not think nitpicking about which frequency band can, and which one can&#39;t be observed without signal processing."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":1,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450822891,"comment_id":70922,"body":"Nice answer; I like that you discussed the difference between action potentials and gradients across scalp cells. (And if I may say, the way you&#39;re wearing the flip-flop hat is exceedingly effective!)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450823187,"comment_id":70925,"body":"@Christiaan It&#39;s not so much which, but that any, oscillations can be observed, readily, without any processing. Processing is only required for observing <i>interesting<\/i> patterns, not for observing neuronal activity."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450823231,"comment_id":70926,"body":"It&#39;s not a big point, I just wouldn&#39;t want anyone getting the impression you can only see neural activity in the EEG if you do preprocessing."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450824134,"comment_id":70927,"body":"@user49102 Gotcha. However, in the end, EEGs are recorded with differential amplification, which is a very powerful way of excluding noise. Implicitly, one of the most common, but most powerful signal processing strategies is baked into the hardware."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":41700,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450824386,"comment_id":70928,"body":"@anongoodnurse - Thanks! But hey, that hat&#39;s supposed to be secret :)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450824993,"comment_id":70929,"body":"&quot;However, in the end, EEGs are recorded with differential amplification, which is a very powerful way of excluding noise&quot; - yes, but Berger could see Alpha, with <i>very<\/i> rudimentary instruments, in 29, before T&#246;nnies introduced the differential amplifier in the mid-30s. (Berger did almost everything wrong that could be done wrong, and he still saw neural activity.)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cfded303185c63e33dc664f3228c4de7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6887/user-49102","reputation":264,"display_name":"user 49102"},"score":0,"post_id":41700,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450827604,"comment_id":70930,"body":"Still a good answer."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450823947,"creation_date":1450816958,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nSmall electrical EEG signals need to be <em>amplified<\/em> and <em>noise-reduced<\/em> to be detectable. Noise reduction techniques include mathematical averaging and signal processing techniques like filtering.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\nNeuronal activity is electrical and generates <strong>potential differences<\/strong> around each neuron. Potential changes generate <strong>electrical fields<\/strong>. These electrical field are what EEG electrodes pick up (Fig. 1). <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/iTmg3.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/iTmg3.jpg\" alt=\"fields\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 1. Electrical field generated by a neuron (top) and the correspodning electromagnetic field (bottom). The former is detected with EEG, the latter with MEG. Source: <a href=\"http://www.ijbem.org/volume4/number2/093.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Picton (2002)<\/a><\/sup> <\/p>\n\n<p>The intervening tissues (<em>dura mater<\/em> and the skull) are not very conductive and indeed cause those potentials to be <strong>weakened<\/strong>. Worse, still, the electrical fields <strong>diffuse<\/strong> on their way to the scalp, meaning that adjacent patches of neurons cannot reliably be distinguished at the scalp. In other words, the <strong>spatial resolution of the EEG is very poor<\/strong>. The small amplitude of the potentials simply needs <strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amplification\" rel=\"nofollow\">signal amplification<\/a><\/strong> to make them measurable. However, as @user49102 points out nicely, background noise is amplified with it. Hence, the magic hat of an <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrophysiological_techniques_for_clinical_diagnosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">electrophysiologist<\/a> may be needed to extract the signal on the scalp from the noise by using noise reduction techniques such as <strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_averaging\" rel=\"nofollow\">signal averaging<\/a><\/strong> and <strong><a href=\"http://erpinfo.org/erplab/erplab-documentation/documentation-archive-for-previous-versions/v3.x-documentation/tutorial/Filtering.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">filtering<\/a><\/strong>. A notable example where signal averaging is used is the event-related potential, or ERP. A stimulus (e.g. a flash of light) is repeatedly presented and the time-locked EEG is repeatedly measured and averaged offline. The random noise is reduced by the averaging process and neat ERP responses can be extracted without much filtering needed. A specialized example is the visual evoked potential, or VEP (Fig. 2):<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/soqOg.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/soqOg.png\" alt=\"VEP\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>VEP. Source <a href=\"http://webvision.med.utah.edu/book/electrophysiology/visually-evoked-potentials/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Creel (2015)<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n\n<p>Your question whether scalp cells (skin cells) have their own electrical responses - Well yes and no. The skin cells do not generate action potentials and feature only steady membrane potentials. Hence, if they are picked up by the electrodes it will only generate a stable offset, i.e., a baseline shift. Nothing to worry about. Neurons feature active potential <em>differences<\/em> through their action potentials, and that is what is picked up - voltage differences.  <\/p>\n\n<p>The low spatial resolution and weak signal means that the activity of single neurons cannot be measured. Instead, the <strong>gross signal from many thousands of neurons is collectively measured<\/strong>. In turn, when those neurons fire randomly, they will cancel each other's responses out and little signal is obtained. The most robust responses are obtained when the brain generates <strong>synchronized oscillatory potentials<\/strong>, for example during <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slow-wave_sleep\" rel=\"nofollow\">slow-wave sleep<\/a> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2824210/\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Roth, 2009)<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>While EEG has poor spatial resolution of EEG, it <strong>excels in the temporal domain<\/strong>. Responses of a few milliseconds can be measured reliably (Fig. 2). As a comparison, fMRI has a temporal resolution in the order of seconds.   <\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>References<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/iTmg3.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">Creel, <em>Visual Evoked Potentials<\/em>, In: <em>Webvision\nThe Organization of the Retina and Visual System<\/em> (2015)<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ijbem.org/volume4/number2/093.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Picton, <em>Int J Bioelectromagnetism<\/em> (2002); <strong>4<\/strong>(2): 225 - 8<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2824210/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Roth, <em>J Clin Sleep Med<\/em> (2009); <strong>5<\/strong>(2 Suppl): S4\u2013S5<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":41700,"question_id":41690,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1450823947}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41690/how-can-neuronal-signals-faithfully-be-reproduced-by-scalp-electrodes","last_activity_date":1450823947,"creation_date":1450766429,"answer_count":2,"title":"How can neuronal signals faithfully be reproduced by scalp electrodes?","body":"<p>There is a skull barrier (and possibly other layers too) between the brain and the scalp. I have seen people trying to extract EEG signals from the scalp by connecting electrodes and interface it to other devices. But how do these weak signals pass through these many barriers and reach the scalp electrodes? Also, \"scalp cells\" will have their own dynamics, right? <\/p>\n\n<p>I simply don't understand <strong><em>how can we even get a approximate measure of electrical signals inside brain from scalp<\/em><\/strong>.<\/p>\n","question_id":41690,"tags":["neuroscience","brain","biophysics","electroencephalography"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":41700,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":78,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1450820939},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcab406e9b130952eaa56048e901054b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20758,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20758/jm97","reputation":242,"display_name":"JM97","accept_rate":75},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450820709,"creation_date":1450820709,"body":"<p>A reservoir host most obviously is a long-term carrier organism of a given pathogen that <strong>doesn't exhibit the disease caused by the pathogen<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>A vector is literally any <em>agent<\/em> that transfers the pathogen to another organism. If you think about it, a reservoir doesn't have to be a vector i.e. there's no route of transmission they participate in, but a vector can certainly be a reservoir, such as bats, who often act as a vector for the pathogens they house (think Rabies). On the flip side, ticks are common vectors for Lyme disease, but small rodents actually act as the reservoir for <em>B. burgdorferi<\/em> (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2592199/\">1<\/a>).<\/p>\n","answer_id":41701,"question_id":41696,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41696/can-a-reservoir-host-act-as-a-vector","last_activity_date":1450820709,"creation_date"