 giving the <a href=\"https://www.ted.com/talks/nathan_wolfe_what_s_left_to_explore/transcript?language=en\" rel=\"nofollow\">Ted talk &quot;Whats left to explore?&quot;<\/a> a read/listen. Admittedly its intended for a non-technical audience and may be a bit dated (from 2012). <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biological_dark_matter\" rel=\"nofollow\">Biological dark matter<\/a> is the corresponding (rather sparse) wiki page."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":0,"post_id":41683,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450822996,"comment_id":70924,"body":"Immunity to many pathogens manifests similarly; there&#39;s enough evidence to discern viral vs. bacterial most of the time, though. Viruses are often self-limiting at that, and end up clearing after a few days, making it relatively pointless to prescribe an antiviral. Flu is tricky, to make things more complicated, since going with an antiviral is really only helpful soon after onset of symptoms."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5deb8de031f80c23f19e9b6d389e5afe?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8918,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8918/slebetman","reputation":271,"display_name":"slebetman"},"score":3,"post_id":41683,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450859271,"comment_id":70937,"body":"To give you a picture of how little we actually know about microorganisms, if you take a soil sample from your back yard you are guaranteed to discover new species of microbes. Someone did this several years back simply to gauge how many more species there are to discover and to his surprise every time he did this experiment he always discover new species. Think about that: always. He could not find any soil sample that only contained known species of microbes."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/986656e4512511a0c55dc91dd218bbeb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18905,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18905/nathan","reputation":1086,"display_name":"Nathan"},"score":25,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450797437,"creation_date":1450757571,"body":"<p>It's a cost/benefit situation.  Yes they could have taken samples, processed them,  teased out the virus, and eventually identified exactly what virus (sort of*) that your girlfriend had by its gene sequence.  But do you want to pay 10k-100k per virus to find that out, or just pay $20-100 and take some fluids and be fine.<\/p>\n\n<p>I say sort of because viruses tend to mutate quite a bit.  A great example is the influenza virus.  There are many strains, with genotyping you can say this is H5N1 vs H1N1.  But typically the result for a person is going to be \"You have the flu. <em>&lt;Insert generic flu advice here.&gt;<\/em>\"<\/p>\n\n<p>There are some tests specific to families, again flu is a great example.  Because the flu virus can be deadly to certain groups of people, and because it affects a lot of people, it's important to have a rapid test for it.  I just got the test today, only took about 15 minutes, thankfully I do not have the flu.<\/p>\n\n<p>But for what I will call everyday cold viruses, there's no need for advanced or rapid detection.  And that's where you get the answer you got today.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41687,"question_id":41683,"up_vote_count":25,"last_edit_date":1450797437},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"score":37,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/tH15z.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"register