rvive the infection. <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/112/15/4719.abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">Little is known about the details of the immune reaction to ebola, but the immune system does get activated<\/a>. The immune system even remains on \"high alert\" for quite some time after infection and recovery.<\/p>\n\n<p>And the antibodies do stick around, <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/transmission/qas.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">at least for 10 years<\/a>. Whether they confer immunity against all strains of ebola, we don't seem to know - ebola isn't very well-researched yet.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41675,"question_id":41674,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1450712412}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41674/how-does-the-body-survive-ebola","last_activity_date":1450726575,"creation_date":1450709929,"answer_count":1,"title":"How does the body survive Ebola?","body":"<p>Because Ebola takes over the immune system and uses it to replicate more and more of the virus, how does the body survive? <\/p>\n\n<p>Is it a case of the virus being self-limiting and eventually just getting 'too big for its britches' so to speak? Or does the body somehow eventually start producing antibodies to fight it off?<\/p>\n","question_id":41674,"tags":["virus","infection","ebola"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":41675,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":true,"view_count":45,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1450726575},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/OKW5r.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20739,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20739/oscar-moya","reputation":16,"display_name":"Oscar Moya"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4897ecd6ff83143f48eebc4d33754652?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19994,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19994/frankyg","reputation":406,"display_name":"FrankyG"},"score":1,"post_id":41673,"edited"