XR1zKCTMHEM<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The second fly could be some male fly, which met the female \"by accident\" and could not mate her.<\/p>\n\n<p>This picture shows a still image (for visualization purpose; the species are different so are the larvae/eggs):<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/zvYBa.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/zvYBa.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>+<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ChkT3.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ChkT3.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.everythingabout.net/articles/biology/animals/arthropods/insects/flies/fruit_fly_laying_egg.shtml\" rel=\"nofollow\">source<\/a> of the last image<\/p>\n\n<p>The \"looped nature\" of GIF image confuses and gives an impression that the flies do the \"ritual\" continuously.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41650,"question_id":41548,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450642123},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450689753,"creation_date":1450688808,"body":"<p>I've been working on fruit flies now for 7-8 years, including a lot of large mating and courtship assays. I believe what you are seeing is the male (identifiable by the black end of the abdomen and different shape) approaching a female. Judging by the extension of the male's right wing in the second still image, he is making a brief courtship attempt, but its very difficult to be certain of that from these images. The female then extends her ovipositor.<\/p>\n\n<p>I believe that this could be one of two things:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>A mate rejection behaviour by females - she actively made the movement to stop the males advances<\/li>\n<li>The female was simply preparing herself for oviposition - the male just happened to approach her<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>I've seen it happen enough times both with females subject to courtship and females not subject to courtship to think that either of those is plausible for what is happening in your clip. Given the possible courtship by the male and the following text &amp; videos from a recent paper I would say it is option 1, a mate rejection.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"Recently mated females reject courting males through a variety of actions such as decamping, flicking their wings, kicking the approaching male, or extrusion of the ovipositor [8]. Thus, copulation switches female behavior from acceptance to rejection.\" <em>- <a href=\"http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0126445\">Kimura et al. 2015<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>and <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>\"Under natural conditions, the <strong>recently mated female occasionally extends the ovipositor straight along her body axis<\/strong> (anterior-posterior axis) <strong>toward the courting male<\/strong> (Fig 1A, S1 Movie), who usually positions himself behind the female [21]. During the ovipositor extension, the female abdomen was width-compressed throughout its entire length. <strong>We refer to the ovipositor extension as mating-type extrusion<\/strong> when it was protruded horizontally along the female body axis. <strong>A mated female that has found a suitable site for oviposition will lower and bend her abdomen downward<\/strong> and insert the ovipositor into the substrate before performing movements to expel an egg that is inserted into the substrate (Fig 1B, S2 Movie) [9]. <strong>Unlike the extrusion for rejection, the female narrowed the abdomen only at its posterior part.<\/strong>\" <em>- <a href=\"http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0126445\">Kimura et al. 2015<\/a><\/em><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>In figures <a href=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/06/Drosophila-Ovipositor-Extension-in-Mating-Behavior-and-Egg-Deposition-Involves-Distinct-Sets-of-pone.0126445.s007.ogv\">S1<\/a> and <a href=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/72/Drosophila-Ovipositor-Extension-in-Mating-Behavior-and-Egg-Deposition-Involves-Distinct-Sets-of-pone.0126445.s008.ogv\">S2<\/a> you can see those two behaviours very clearly in videos. <\/p>\n\n<p><em>Note, I came to my answer before finding this Kimura paper so that's two lines of independent evidence (my experience and their paper). I hope it answers your question.<\/em><\/p>\n","answer_id":41670,"question_id":41548,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1450689753}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41548/what-are-these-two-fruit-flies-doing","last_activity_date":1450689753,"creation_date":1450198421,"answer_count":2,"title":"What are these two fruit flies doing?","body":"<p>When taking some pictures I accidentally captured two fruit flies doing this:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/4Oid8.gif\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/4Oid8.gif\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The photos are unfortunately blurry, but from what I can tell, one fly approaches the other from behind, and something is then retracted/pulled into the front fly's body. I'm guessing it has to do with reproduction, but it doesn't look like the fruit fly mating I've seen before.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here are some stills from the sequence:\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/67my8.png\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/67my8.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a> \n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qUqQL.png\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qUqQL.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/1ZE6H.png\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/1ZE6H.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a>\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/FS4nx.png\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/FS4nx.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":41548,"tags":["entomology","ethology","drosophila"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":41670,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":118,"up_vote_count":8},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/x30jD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20642,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20642/minnow","reputation":413,"display_name":"Minnow"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9b6a39ad5c91ec750189b71a6122af94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19679,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19679/user19679","reputation":286,"display_name":"user19679"},"score":0,"post_id":41634,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450646855,"comment_id":70808,"body":"it might be due to irritation of muscular tissue, causing slight disfunction of the mechanism that controls the bladder/urine flow? (the urgency). The frequency might be down to irritation in the urethra and hence the need for release increases but, also the bodies &quot;desperation&quot; to expel the urine in order to excrete the bacteria by the medium, urine."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/x30jD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20642,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20642/minnow","reputation":413,"display_name":"Minnow"},"score":1,"post_id":41664,"edited":false,"creation_date":1451179956,"comment_id":71109,"body":"@Medica I presume?  Nice answer, you are well-rounded!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8bbc94977312d285045b2412257b6cb8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1195,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1195/kenorb","reputation":285,"display_name":"kenorb","accept_rate":67},"score":0,"post_id":41664,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461696178,"comment_id":79949,"body":"Any links to the sources?"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450685624,"creation_date":1450668682,"body":"<p>Nerve endings exist in a more or less homeostatic interstitial fluid medium which when disturbed in certain ways result in depolarization. This is a very simple explanation, but basically correct. Depending on the nerves being discussed, a change in the medium can be the presence/absence of neurotransmitters (serotonin, GABA, etc.), chemicals released from damaged tissue, pH differences, etc. etc.<\/p>\n\n<p>Very simply put, anything causing irritation of the bladder or urethral mucosa will cause some of the nerve endings to depolarize; these are some of the same nerves that depolarize when the bladder is full, and therefore the sensation is of urgency (the feeling that one needs to urinate). The substances can be substances excreted by bacteria, released by neutrophils, or some other.<\/p>\n\n<p>Simply administering a topical anesthetic - something that decreases the depolarization of nerve endings by reversibly binding to/inactivating sodium channels - (lidocaine, for example) will instantly alleviate this sensation. In the case of UTIs, a commonly given medication is the bladder anesthetic phenazopyridine hydrochloride.<\/p>\n\n<p>The more complex answer is that no one <em>exactly<\/em> knows. The complexity is more important in the treatment of non-infectious causes of urinary urgency and in the investigation of why catheter-related UTI are often <em>asymptomatic<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Edited to add: If you're looking for a more teleological reason (such as, it hurts so that you'll get flush out the bacteria faster, that's not actually what happens. When it hurts to urinate, very many women intuitively stop drinking fluids in an attempt to avoid the pain of urination, allowing the infection to get much worse. The counterintuitive measure is to drink more, not less, to flush out bacteria.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41664,"question_id":41634,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1450685624}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41634/why-does-a-urinary-tract-infection-cause-a-strong-persistent-urge-to-urinate","last_activity_date":1450685624,"creation_date":1450535581,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does a Urinary Tract Infection cause a strong, persistent urge to urinate?","body":"<p>There are plenty of articles on the fact the a urinary tract infection (UTI) causes frequent and urgent urination. For example; on this <a href=\"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003140.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">National Institutes of Health webpage<\/a>.  <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>My question is:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Why does a urinary tract infection cause an increased desire and hence, a greater urgency to urinate?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":41634,"tags":["human-biology","pathology","infection"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":41664,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":68,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1450649261},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/352620ba41c077bb6cf636b59bfd2fd3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17427,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17427/pi5","reputation":311,"display_name":"Pi5","accept_rate":25},"closed_date":1450776427,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pVoco.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14587/the-nightman","reputation":1330,"display_name":"The Nightman","accept_rate":50},"score":1,"post_id":37044,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440173398,"comment_id":62052,"body":"Could you provide a reference to the article that you read that in? I want to look at what was said before answering."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/352620ba41c077bb6cf636b59bfd2fd3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17427,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17427/pi5","reputation":311,"display_name":"Pi5","accept_rate":25},"score":0,"post_id":37044,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pVoco.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14587,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14587/the-nightman","reputation":1330,"display_name":"The Nightman","accept_rate":50},"edited":false,"creation_date":1440173619,"comment_id":62053,"body":"I was just reading about cancers in my book trueman..and also searched how many types of cancer were there but no heart cancer was found so I asked"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":1,"post_id":37044,"edited":false,"creation_date":1440209546,"comment_id":62092,"body":"@Pi5 just to let you know, the answer you marked as correct is, in fact, not. You can see my comment below it for more info."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":1,"post_id":37044,"edited":false,"creation_date":1442902331,"comment_id":65004,"body":"What do you mean by &quot;myogenic heart cells&quot; precisely? As I understand it, &quot;myogenic&quot; refers to a precursor cell (myoblast, myotube etc), as opposed to a fully developed cardiomyocyte. Such myogenic cells are mainly present during early development --- are you thinking of a childhood cancer of the heart?"