MR - hormones don&#39;t make chickens lay eggs; breed, light and temperature do. A mature chicken will lay 300+ eggs a year given long days (that means artificial light in the winter) and enough food and some help with temperatures (less energy lost to maintain body heat), Some lay ~360 (obviously referred to as layer breeds, like white leghorns.) There is another question answered already on hormones and eggs. Chickens don&#39;t need them. When they slow down, they get replaced. It&#39;s just cheaper."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":1,"post_id":41658,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450651537,"comment_id":70813,"body":"@AMR - If you want to ask that (separate) question, though, since I answered for broilers but not layers, I&#39;d be happy to answer it."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41658,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450651725,"comment_id":70814,"body":"@anongoodnurse Interesting... So conditions affect nesting behavior and nesting behavior drives egg production."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stacke