id -- which should be about a week after natural selection is first mentioned -- it simply becomes an exercise in semantics.  If you read actual papers by actual evolutionary biologists, they pretty much all use shorthand language like this.  We&#39;re all grownups here."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3f80897d57525afe9eac4fb8c8318052?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6427,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6427/user2357112","reputation":101,"display_name":"user2357112"},"score":1,"post_id":41614,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450582014,"comment_id":70780,"body":"@iayork: I don&#39;t think it&#39;s safe to assume the questioner <i>is<\/i> past that very early introductory stage. Even if they are, this answer will probably be read by people who aren&#39;t past that stage."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1450467369,"creation_date":1450467369,"body":"<p>Fish are definitely evolving to avoid fishing pressure. For example, <a href=\"http://jacksonville.com/sports/outdoors/2009-10-04/story/study_avoid_hook_an_inherited_trait_in_largemouth_bass\">largemouth bass evolve toward avoiding hooks<\/a>.  More broadly, since fishing selectively removes larger fish from the population, there's selection toward <a href=\"http://labs.biology.ucsd.edu/roy/documents/FenbergandRoy08.pdf\">fish evolving smaller size<\/a>.  A brief review, linking to many studies demonstrating this, is <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2924707/\">Evolutionary impacts of fishing: overfishing's \u2018Darwinian debt\u2019<\/a>.   <\/p>\n","answer_id":41614,"question_id":41613,"up_vote_count":14},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[