hange.com/users/20645/snazzy-sanoj","reputation":215,"display_name":"Snazzy Sanoj"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1450528150,"comment_id":70758,"body":"@SnazzySanoj:  Recent human fishing pressure has caused fish to evolve  dramatically, as is pointed out in the multiple references in my answer.  Evolution takes time when the selection pressure is low, as is the case for most &quot;natural&quot; situations.  When the selection pressure is very strong, as with modern fishing methods, evolution can proceed quite rapidly.  Hence, we now see many species of food fish that reach a much smaller maximum size, for example."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":41624,"edited":false,"creation_date":1457422641,"comment_id":76550,"body":"Please could you add some supporting scientific material that reinforces your answer and allows further reading."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1450492033,"creation_date":1450492033,"body":"<p>As iayork stated, fish have indeed evolved strategies to cope with fishing pressures. The problem is that evolution takes time, and humans are constantly inventing new fishing strategies. A thousand years ago, people caught fish by hand or with simple nets. Today, the fishing industry uses giant trawlers, sonar and other techniques.<\/p>\n\n<p>At the same time, fish have to cope with increasing pollution and other environmental disturbances. Many fisheries have already been wiped out.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41624,"question_id":41613,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41613/are-fishes-evolving","last_activity_date":1450492033,"creation_date":1450466547,"answer_count":2,"title":"Are fishes evolving?","body":"<p>As far as I know, Fishing has been one of 