"edited":false,"creation_date":1418703648,"comment_id":41328,"body":"&quot;oligodendrocytes ... wrap themselves to form the insulting myelin sheath&quot; - wait, what? TIL."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/PObJM.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4264,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4264/jan-dvorak","reputation":101,"display_name":"Jan Dvorak"},"score":1,"post_id":25889,"edited":false,"creation_date":1418704130,"comment_id":41331,"body":"Not only that, I didn&#39;t know the myelin sheath is formed by having some extra cells migrate into place. I thought they were acellular and grew from the axon?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":25889,"edited":false,"creation_date":1418704217,"comment_id":41332,"body":"Yep, they are definitely cellular - follow the citing link, grab any neuroscience textbook, or everyone&#39;s best pal wikipedia: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myelin\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myelin<\/a>. Thanks for the typo though :)"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1418703773,"creation_date":1418642942,"body":"<p>The question is relatively broad and one should take into account that the brain not only consists of <em>neurons<\/em>, but also <em>glial cells<\/em> (supportive cells) and <em>pre-mitotic neuronal stem cells<\/em>. Furthermore, as critical fellow-scientists have indicated, developmental stage is very important, as the developing embryonic brain is very different from the adult brain.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, after sifting through various publications, the answer to the question is actually remarkably simple: <strong>Yes, brain cells migrate.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>In  the <strong>adult brain<\/strong> glial cells migrate in the brain (<a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v10/n11/abs/nrn2720.html\">KlÃ¤mbt, 2009<\/a>). Glial cells are involved in a myriad of functions, but a notable example of migrating glial cells are the oligodendrocytes that migrate relative long distances to find their target axons onto which they wrap themselves to form the insulating myelin sheath (<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0166223600020968\">Tsai and Miller, 2002<\/a>).  <\/p>\n\n<p>Neuronal stem cells migrate over long distances in response to injury (<a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/101/52/18117.full.pdf+html\">Imitola et al., 2004<\/a>) and they migrate from specific stem-cell locations (e.g., hippocampus and subventricular zone) to other regions (<a href=\"http://www.nature.com/bmt/journal/v32/n1s/full/1703937a.html\">Clarke, 2003<\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>Interestingly, post-mitotic (fully differentiated, not-dividing) neurons can also be migratory in the adult brain. Specifically, newly formed neurons can migrate over hundreds of microns in fish (<a href=\"http://www.jneurosci.org/content/32/4/1436.full\">Scott et al., 2012<\/a>) and neuronal migration has been shown in the human cortex as well (<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0896627300806510\">Fox et al., 1998<\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>Not surprisingly, glial cells, stem cells and neurons also migrate during <strong>embryonic development<\/strong>. Most notably, post-mitotic neurons destined to fulfill peripheral functions have to migrate over relatively long distances from the neural crest to their target locations (<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10831/\">Neuroscience, 2<sup>nd<\/sup> ed, Neuronal Migration<\/a>).  <\/p>\n","answer_id":25889,"question_id":25880,"up_vote_count":50,"last_edit_date":1418703773},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/qHvmd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5009,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5009/copperkettle","reputation":213,"display_name":"CopperKettle","accept_rate":80},"score":7,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450456459,"creation_date":1419535156,"body":"<p>To add to Christiaan's answer, I'll mention one striking example of long-distance neuronal migration in the adult mammalian brain: the so-called <strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rostral_migratory_stream\" rel=\"nofollow\">Rostral Migratory Stream<\/a><\/strong> found in rodents, in rabbits and both the squirrel and rhesus monkey. <\/p>\n\n<p>Neuronal precursors originating in the subventricular zone (SVZ) of the brain migrate to reach the main olfactory bulb (OB), and it's quite a distance for the small cells.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/KmAvj.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n","answer_id":26185,"question_id":25880,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1450456459}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/25880/can-brain-cells-move","last_activity_date":1450456459,"creation_date":1418625333,"answer_count":2,"title":"Can brain cells move?","body":"<p>I was discussing this with my brother. I'm pretty sure I read somewhere that they can move.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks<\/p>\n\n<p>EDIT: By movement I mean long distance migration (preferably within the brain only).<\/p>\n","question_id":25880,"tags":["cell-biology","neuroscience","brain","development","stem-cells"],"score":35,"accepted_answer_id":25889,"down_vote_count":1,"protected_date":1421837938,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2423,"up_vote_count":36,"last_edit_date":1450280568},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a0133b940943505144c6f725daa12918?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19494,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19494/user19494","reputation":16,"display_name":"user19494"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":39757,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445233322,"comment_id":66636,"body":"I edited your title such that it summarizes your actual question. Let me know if that is fine."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1445238815,"creation_date":1445236745,"body":"<p>You should understand that the body is an open system which is held at a steady state. Water can diffuse in and out of the cell such that the osmolarity is balanced on both sides of the membranes. If the water potential changes in either of these compartments (intra- and extra- cellular) because of addition or removal of water molecules, both the compartments would be affected such that finally the osmolarity is same in both the compartments. It may, however, take some time to achieve the steady state. <\/p>\n\n<p>If you refer to sweating when you say \"activity\" then you should note that it is a complex process with extensive neurological control. The water that is secreted by the eccrine sweat gland primarily comes from the blood. However, profuse sweating will lead to water loss from both the intra- and extra- cellular compartments.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Prolonged exposure to hyperthermic conditions and/or prolonged\n  exercise in the heat can induce water deficits due to profuse\n  sweating, resulting in hypohydration. This water deficit lowers both\n  intracellular and extracellular volumes and results in plasma\n  hyperosmolality and hypovolemia; both of which impair sweating.\n  <hr>\n  <sub><em>Shibasaki, Manabu, and Craig G. Crandall. \"<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20036977\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>Mechanisms and controllers of eccrine sweating in humans.<\/strong><\/a>\" Frontiers in bioscience (Scholar edition) 2 (2010): 685-696.<\/em><\/sub><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><br>\nSo, for your experiment it is better to measure the osmolarity of the extracellular fluid or the blood plasma because:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>It is easier to measure<\/li>\n<li>It would not be sensitive to local and temporary effects<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":39759,"question_id":39757,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1445238815}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39757/which-is-more-susceptible-to-dehydration-extracellular-and-intracellular-fluid","last_activity_date":1450424820,"creation_date":1445231802,"answer_count":1,"title":"Which is more susceptible to dehydration \u2014 extracellular and intracellular fluid?","body":"<p>I want to ask in human body, there is intracellular and extracellular fluid that makes up the total body water of our body, which is drained first when we do activities? extra or intra? if I want to do a bioimpedance measurement, does measuring only the extracellular fluid good? Thankyou<\/p>\n","question_id":39757,"tags":["physiology"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":79,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1445233276},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/be76b939479b155f5ffe5eef9afeeff5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20672,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20672/chubakueno","reputation":178,"display_name":"chubakueno"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":2,"post_id":41581,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450322145,"comment_id":70604,"body":"Likely has to do with how the injection will drain into the lymphatic system. <a href=\"http://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/2