em>Short Tandem Repeat<\/em> (STR)<\/a>. They are common sources of variations in genes because the DNA matching process during <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">meiosis<\/a> sometimes \"slips\" one or two repeats over.<\/p>\n\n<p>The type of test performed by 23andMe reports values for selected SNPs (Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms).  SNPs are a different kind of variation from STRs, so the data available from 23andMe does not allow you to determine the kind of IGF1 (CA)<sub>n<\/sub> variant present.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41601,"question_id":41591,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41591/understanding-different-genetic-terminology-genotype-vs-snp","last_activity_date":1450403228,"creation_date":1450373742,"answer_count":1,"title":"Understanding different genetic terminology - Genotype vs SNP","body":"<p>I recently came across a study that refereed to variations in genes like this:<\/p>\n\n<p>IGF1 (CA)19/(CA)19, IGF1(CA)19/X, IGF1 X/X<\/p>\n\n<p>(From this study: <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3274549/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3274549/<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<p>I wanted to know, as a member of 23andme, how I could check these \"markers\" (?) against the SNP's listed in 23andme.<\/p>\n\n<p>I would be very grateful for any help.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks.<\/p>\n","question_id":41591,"tags":["gene","snp"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":41601,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":40,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1450403228},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0bb6c1fe7aae72712db2c434a23f8ec4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":20689,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20689/sclamons","reputation":1,"display_name":"sclamons"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchang