 reading the answers a few times over, I just moved on because I couldn't figure out how to answer. My first instinct said that both (b) and (d) were correct, but the answer is (e).<\/p>\n\n<p>After some thought, I've come to a few ideas how this could be true.<br>\n1. The wording is incorrect, the definition he provides for protostomia says \"body cavity formed by schizocoely,\" and \"spiral determinate cleavage.\"<br>\n2. These two characteristics are not present in all protostomes (i.e. spiralia evolves after ecdysozoa, and platyzoa have no body cavity).<\/p>\n\n<p>Just looking for some clarity or closure regarding this.<\/p>\n","question_id":41600,"tags":["zoology","taxonomy","phylogenetics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":24,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450397525},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/WqpNM.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18659,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18659/oraclecell","reputation":16,"display_name":"OracleCell"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450392307,"creation_date":1450391535,"body":"<p>Saltatory conduction is faster, because between nodes, the action potential skips the intervening distance. There, passive spread of charge takes over, which is much faster.<\/p>\n\n<p>The optimal internode distance for speed of action potential transmission is that distance where the depolarization currents just do not die out before reaching the next node through passive charge conduction. A bit further, and the depolarization current of one node doesn't reach the next. A bit shorter and more nodes are necessary per unit of axon length, slowing down saltatory conduction. <\/p>\n\n<p>In other words, your notion that more nodes speed up transmission is incorrect. On the contrary, less nodes speed up transmission. The extreme case is no nodes at all, where a continuous channel density lines the axon (an approximately infinite number of nodes). This is identical to normal, slow action potential transmission. <\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Further reading<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14249/saltatory-conduction-of-nerve-impulses\">Saltatory conduction of nerve impulses<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/8282/why-is-saltatory-conduction-faster-than-continuous-conduction\">Why is saltatory conduction faster than continuous conduction?<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":41596,"question_id":39554,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1450392307}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39554/does-the-number-of-nodes-determines-the-rate-at-which-a-neural-signal-is-transmi","last_activity_date":1450392719,"creation_date":1444764560,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does the number of nodes determines the rate at which a neural signal is transmitted?","body":"<p>I know that the the bigger the neuron's diameter is, the faster the neuron signal is transmitted. This makes sense according to the proportionality of resistance to the inverse of area and thus, in physics, there is lower resistance in wires that have bigger diameters (cross-sectional areas). I can imagine that this is the same logic for our neurons as well because they are like wires. I also know that the more myelinated a neuron is, the faster the neuron signal travels too because myelination acts as an insulation that reduces resistance in signal transmission. <\/p>\n\n<p>But then, my question is: does the number of nodes matter and affect the rate at which a neural signal is transmitted? Can you please help explain why or why not? Let's say for example, that two neurons have same amount of diameter and myelinated sheaths hypothetically, but one of them has more nodes. Does that number of nodes of ranvier make the saltatory conduction faster? <\/p>\n","question_id":39554,"tags":["neuroscience","neurophysiology"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":31,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1450392719},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a2066f3ec0aaa1cf0f3b9ef8425e5f72?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16339,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16339/viv","reputation":50,"display_name":"Viv"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":39768,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445295322,"comment_id":66692,"body":"I edited the question quite substantially. In its original state it was quite unclear what you were asking. However, if this version clashes with your original intentions feel free to roll back. +1"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1450390759,"creation_date":1450347610,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nThe pain withdrawal reflex can only be suppressed when touching something painful on purpose. Deliberate, conscious contraction of the extensor muscle <em>before<\/em> reflex initiation can prevent the contraction of the flexor muscles once the reflex is started.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\nThe pain withdrawal reflex arc (Fig. 1) receives input from sensory neurons that enter the dorsal part of the spinal cord via the dorsal root of the spinal nerve and synapse onto interneurons within the spinal gray matter. The interneurons in turn synapse onto motor neurons, which send axons that exit the cord via the ventral root. They conduct information to the muscles. The resulting withdrawal reflex is initiated by activating motor neurons of the flexor muscles (agonist), and simultaneous inhibition of the motor neurons to the extensor muscles (antagonist). This loosening of the antagonist while the agonist is being contracted is referred to as <em>reciprocal inhibition<\/em> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8299401\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Crone, 1993)<\/a>. More important to the question is the fact that the <strong><em>motor response is well under way before<\/em><\/strong> the signals responsible for the <strong><em>conscious sensation of pain<\/em><\/strong> (which exit the reflex pathway in the spinal cord) ever reach the brain (<a href=\"https://www.biog1445.org/demo/09/reflexarc.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Cornell University<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/lVbCV.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/lVbCV.png\" alt=\"![reflex arc\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 1. Schematic of the pain withdrawal reflex arc. Source: <a href=\"http://courses.washington.edu/conj/motor/spinalreflexes.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">Washington Uni<\/a>.<\/sup> <\/p>\n\n<p>Hence, the reflex pathway is initiated even before we are aware of any pain. The only possible way to suppress a reflex that is faster than perception is to start counteracting the agonist (flexor) before the reflex is initiated, i.e., by contracting the antagonist (extensor) before touching the painful object. <\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Reference<\/strong><\/sub><br>\n<sub><strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8299401\" rel=\"nofollow\">Crone, <em>Dan Med Bull<\/em> (1993); <strong>40<\/strong>(5): 571-81<\/a><\/sub> <\/p>\n","answer_id":41584,"question_id":39768,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1450390759}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39768/how-are-reflexes-suppressed","last_activity_date":1450390759,"creation_date":1445265397,"answer_count":1,"title":"How are reflexes suppressed?","body":"<p>What neurophysiological process keeps reflex arcs in check? For example, the withdrawal reflex causes the hand to jerk back when the fingers touch something painfully hot incidentally. However, that reflex can be voluntarily suppressed when one <em>deliberately<\/em> touches that same hot object on purpose. What neural process is involved in conscious suppression of reflexes?<\/p>\n","question_id":39768,"tags":["neuroscience","neurophysiology","central-nervous-system","reflexes"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":41584,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":200,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1445295092},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/641b61f04fb0b18f03f27f9f74f385eb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20676,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20676/pwghost","reputation":28,"display_name":"pwghost"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"post_id":41583,"edited":false,"creation_date":1450347857,"comment_id":70620,"body":"Welcome to Bio. Are you searching for research on folks that claim to be able to sense another person&#39;s pain by touching them? Please improve the wording of your post, it is unintelligible now."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/641b61f04fb0b18f03f27f9f74f385eb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20676,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20676/pwghost","reputation":28,"display_name":"pwghost"},"score":0,"post_id":41583,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":